N2  - Introduction: Literature suggests that young stroke survivors report a range of cognitive impairments in Executive Functioning (EF), and this may have a range of impacts on activities of daily living. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) has been shown to improve EF among stroke survivors, but this has not been assessed in a younger cohort. Method: This experimental pilot study utilises tDCS alongside a series of cognitive training tasks (e.g., Digit Span) on young stroke survivors (n=7) and healthy controls (n=13) across a two-week period. The following measures were assessed pre-|post-intervention (where applicable)∗: Trail Making Test (TMT), Stroop Colour Word Test (SCWT), Oxford Cognitive Screen (OCS), Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HADS), Stroke Impact Scale (SIS)∗and National Institutes of Health Stroke Scale (NIHSS)∗. Paired samples and independent samples t-tests were conducted in order to detect significant improvements in outcome measures post-intervention. Results: Preliminary results indicated significant improvements in TMTA [p=0.003] and TMTB [p=0.003] scores in healthy controls and SIS-Communication [p=0.00] scores in young stroke survivors. Whether these results are a result of a learning effect or the direct effect of tDCS remains inconclusive, likely due to the small sample size and corrections for multiple comparisons. Conclusions: Though limited results indicate the effectiveness of tDCS and cognitive training on EF in young stroke survivors of this pilot study, there may be promise for this intervention in a clinical trial. Before this however, it is the recommendation of this pilot that a feasibility study be conducted next before proceeding further.
