N2  - Background: Transcranial photobiomodulation (tPBM) is an emerging noninvasive neuromodulation technique using nearinfrared light and is able to penetrate the cerebral cortex to enhance blood flow and cognition. tPBM may serve as a complementary intervention for individuals with major depressive disorder (MDD) who have poor response or intolerance to other treatments. MDD subjects have demonstrated aberrant intrinsic brain activity in the frontal cortex, as indicated by altered fractional amplitude of low-frequency fluctuations (fALFF). In our proof-of-concept analysis, we aimed to explore the directly irradiated and non-directly irradiated effects of tPBM (pulse (PW) or continuous wave (CW) doses, versus sham) on intrinsic brain activity in individuals with MDD. Methods: We enrolled 10 participants (mean age 36 years, 70% female), who met diagnostic criteria for MDD (MINI) of at least moderate severity (IDS-C score ≥ 23). Using tPBM with concurrent MRI, we examined the change in intrinsic brain activity in frontal regions, directly irradiated by tPBM, and regions not directly irradiated by tPBM. Intrinsic brain activity was measured by fALFF, which is a noninvasive MRI measure of regional, voxel-wise, spontaneous fluctuations of the BOLD signal and is a marker of target engagement with tPBM in individuals with cognitive impairment. Study visits included three sequential resting state MRI scans (3T Siemens Trio and 12 channel head coil) baseline/pre tPBM, during tPBM, and (immediately) post tPBM with multi-echo echo planar imaging (EPI) with the following parameters: TR = 2.5 s; TE = 12.8, 32.33, 51.04 ms; slice thickness 2.5 mm. In addition, a structural T1 scan was acquired. tPBM (Litecure) was delivered in the MRI scanner using bilateral laser probes placed over the participants' forehead during the middle (second) MRI acquisition. All subjects participated in three separate study visits consisting of sham, CW tPBM (300 mW/cm 2), and PW tPBM (900 mW/cm 2 max irradiance, 300 mW/cm 2 average irradiance), in randomized order. Standard EEG electrode positions were directly irradiated, including Fp2 and Fp1 (frontal poles), F4 and F3 (dorsolateral prefrontal cortices), and Fz and Fpz (medial frontal cortices). fMRI data were pre-processed using afni-proc.py and FreeSurfer was used to pre-process the structural scan. fALFF was calculated using afni 3dRSFC and then values were extracted from regions of interest (ROI) using Marsbar. The ROIs consisted of 5mm spheres centered on the cortical MRI coordinates of the irradiated regions. fALFF was extracted from each ROI and gray matter, and then was compared using paired samples t-tests to determine (1) directly irradiated and (2) non-directly irradiated/gray matter changes pre, during, and post tPBM across doses. Voxel-wise paired t-tests were conducted in SPM12 to (3) further parse distal changes regionally. These results were compared amongst doses to (4) understand the optimal tPBM parameters in MDD. Results: (1) Irradiated Regional Effects: For the CW dose, we found a large effect size for the changes in fALFF from baseline to during tPBM (t = 2.27, p = 0.04; Cohen's d= 0.9) within the right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dLPFC). However, due to the small sample size, some of these results did not survive after multiple comparisons correction. Other regions irradiated using the CW demonstrated non-significant decreases in fALFF from baseline to during irradiation and baseline to post irradiation (d < .42 for all). For the PW and sham tPBM doses, we found minimal changes in fALFF (d < .2 for all, p = N.S.). No other irradiated regions showed significant differences when comparing pre to during, and pre to post conditions in CW tPBM. (2) Non-irradiated Gray Matter Effects: We found a decrease of fALFF in gray matter from baseline to during CW (d =.57, p = N.S.), which then increased post tPBM (d =.79, p = N.S.) somewhat towards baseline fALFF levels. (3) Nonirradiated Regional Effects: Using a post hoc voxel-wise paired ttest, we found decreased fALFF in non-irradiated regions including the left thalamus, left caudate, right angular, right medial frontal, and right medial temporal regions, from pre- to during CW (p < 0.005, cluster size k = 100). (4) Parameters: fALFF changes were seen after CW, but not PW and sham. Conclusions: This is the first direct comparison of fALFF in different tPBM doses in a clinical population, a first step towards determining optimal parameters for clinical practice. (1) We found a large effect size for the change in fALFF in right dLPFC from the baseline to during tPBM. Right dLPFC hyperactivity has been previously associated with depression severity and with clinical responses to other types of neuromodulation (e.g., TMS). Our preliminary results indicate that 'hyperactive' regions may serve as useful modifiable markers in MDD using tPBM, and suggest fALFF could help optimize tPBM parameters. (2) The decreases in fALFF were not limited to the directly irradiated brain areas, but also present (with lower effect size) in farther regions, suggesting that biological and clinical effects of tPBM can involve non-irradiated regions of the brain. (3) Voxel-wise analyses showed a right lateralized response to CW tPBM, which may be preliminary evidence of a lateralized effect, consistent with previously established right-hemisphere abnormalities seen in MDD. (4) While changes in fALFF with CW dose were expected, the null findings in the PW were surprising; this increases our understanding of optimal parameters for tPBM in MDD.
