N2  - Background: Post-stroke cognitive impairment can reduce patients' self-care ability and increase disability and mortality but there is no uniform standard for its treatment. In this study, rTMS combined with synchronous working memory training was proposed to improve patients' cognitive function. Methods: A total of 100 stroke patients who were hospitalized and outpatients in the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine, Hongqi Hospital Affiliated to Mudanjiang Medical College from January 2022 to May 2023 were selected and divided into a synchronous group, a repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation group, a working memory training group, and a control group using the random number table method. For cognitive function, the synchronous group was given simultaneous repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation and working memory training, the repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation group was given repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation treatment, the working memory training group was given working memory training, and the control group was not given cognitive training. Before and after treatment, the four groups were given Stroop test, Riverhead behavioral memory test, MoCA test, modified Barthel index test, and Fugl-Meyer test. Results: Before treatment, there was no significant difference in test scores among the four groups (P>0.05). After treatment, the accuracy rate of the baseline phase of the Stroop test in the synchronization group was significantly higher than that in the other three groups (0.86 ± 0.16 vs. 0.75 ± 0.17 vs. 0.72 ± 0.20 vs. 0.64 ± 0.20, P < 0.05); the accuracy rate of the conflict phase of the Stroop test in the synchronization group was significantly higher than that in the other three groups (0.80 ± 0.18 vs. 0.67 ± 0.18 vs. 0.62 ± 0.22 vs. 0.59 ± 0.23, P < 0.05); the reaction time of the baseline phase was significantly shorter than that in the working memory training group and the control group (P < 0.05); the reaction time of the conflict phase was significantly shorter than that in the control group (P < 0.05). In the Rivermead behavioral memory test, MoCA test, modified Barthel test, and Fugl-Meyer test, the synchronization group scored significantly higher than the other three groups (P < 0.05). Conclusions: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation combined with synchronous working memory training can effectively improve the cognitive function of stroke patients..
