N2  - Introduction: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic, degenerative disease of the central nervous system, often leading to cognitive impairment in approximately 65% of patients. This impairment affects cognitive processing speed, learning, and memory, linked to grey matter atrophy and disrupted neural networks. Transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) is a non-invasive technique that can modulate brain rhythms and has shown promise in enhancing cognitive functions. This study aimed to investigate whether tACS could improve working memory, verbal memory, and processing speed in MS patients. We assessed if these effects were present online or persisted offline and correlated cognitive changes with EEG-measured brain rhythm modifications. Methods: We enrolled 23 pwMS with impairment in at least one of the following domains: working memory, information processing speed, and verbal memory. Patients underwent two randomized sessions of gamma-tACS and sham-tACS, spaced at least one week apart. Neuropsychological evaluations were conducted at three time points: baseline (T0), during tACS (T1), and immediately after tACS (T2). Cognitive functions were assessed using DSBW, SDMT, and RAVL test. EEG recordings were taken at the beginning and end of each session. Gamma-tACS was delivered at 40 Hz for 30 minutes, while shamtACS involved a brief 7-second stimulation. EEG analyses included connectivity and power spectral density measurements. Results: Regarding the clinical assessment, we found a significant Time∗Intervention interaction across all domains. Post hoc analysis using Bonferroni correction revealed that, concerning the comparison of scores at the three time points, the score at baseline differed from that during tACS (showing improvement) only for SOP and WM. However, post-stimulation, there was no difference between sham and real conditions, except for a potential trend (p=0.08) observed in WM. From EEG measurements, we observed, Speed of Processing (SOP), power analysis showed significance for intervention (p=0.050; F=4.700) and frequency (p=0.000; F=48.490), while the intervention x frequency interaction was not significant (p=0.500; F=0.735). For Working Memory (WM) connectivity, significance was found for time (p=0.030; F=8.330) and frequency (p=0.007; F=21.050). Verbal Memory (VM) connectivity analysis revealed significance only for frequency (p=0.015; F=13.260). Discussion: From the comparison of clinical and neurophysiological results, despite changes in power and connectivity immediately after stimulation, especially in SOP, the greatest effect appears to occur during stimulation, where EEG recording was not feasible. Conclusions: In conclusion, tACS may be considered a potential nonpharmacological approach for treating cognitive impairments in pwMS.
