N2  - Background and Aims: Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) has garnered attention over the past thirty years as a potential enhancer of both motor and non-motor functions in neurological disorders, with a particular focus on its application in the cerebellum. Cerebellar tDCS can modulate neural networks, influencing pathological activity, and integrating motor and non-motor functions. However, the clinical utility and optimal parameters of cerebellar tDCS remain unclear and controversial. To synthesize and map the existing literature concerning the application of cerebellar tDCS in CNS disorders. Methods: A search was conducted in electronic databases including Scopus, MEDLINE, CINAHL, ProQuest Dissertations and Theses, and Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. Studies published in English, examining the effects of cerebellar tDCS in CNS disorders in adult populations were included. Results: 2,962 articles were identified through the search. Following fulltext screening, 35 articles were deemed relevant for inclusion, comprising 18 RCTs and 3 systematic review studies. These studies investigated the effects of cerebellar tDCS in various CNS disorders, including Ataxia, Stroke, Parkinson's disease, Multiple Sclerosis, Dystonia, Essential Tremor, Vestibular disorder, Huntington's Disease, and Cerebellar degeneration. Conclusions: Cerebellar tDCS semerges as a promising intervention for recovery in CNS disorders, demonstrating potential benefits for both motor and non-motor functions. Specifically, improvements have been observed in motor functions such as gait speed, balance, visual tracking, and reaction time, as well as non-motor functions including emotion perception, mood, and attention. Further research is warranted to elucidate the full extent of cerebellar tDCS efficacy and to advance its management in disorders like Ataxia, Stroke, and Parkinson's disease.
