N2  - Background and Aims: Stroke is a significant cause of disability, leading to cognitive decline and various physical and emotional issues. Mindfulness and transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) are potential interventions for improving cognitive and depressive symptoms in stroke patients. This study assesses the effectiveness of mindfulness-based intervention and tDCS on cognitive performance and depression status in stroke patients. Methods: In this clinical trial, 30 stroke patients were randomly assigned to mindfulness, tDCS, or control groups. tDCS involved ten sessions of 2 milliamperes (mA) direct current for 20 minutes. The mindfulness group underwent eight sessions of 2.5 hours program, following a stress reduction program based on Kabat-Zinn mindfulness training. Cognitive and depression status were measured using the Addenbrooke's Cognitive Examination questionnaire and Beck Depression Inventory (BDI) questionnaire, respectively before and after each intervention. Results: Although there was a significant difference in the BDI score of the participants in the mindfulness and control groups before the intervention period (p=0.04) and after the intervention period (p=0.04), BDI score changes didn't have a significant difference (p=0.78). The participants in the tDCS group had a greater improvement in ACE score changes before and after the intervention period in comparison to the control group (p=0.01). Conclusions: Mindfulness does not significantly improve the cognitive and depression status in stroke patients. However, patients who received tDCS demonstrated a significant improvement in cognitive status compared to the control group. In this study, tDCS effectively enhanced cognitive domains, fluency, and memory in stroke patients.
