N2  - Background and Aims: Patterned Sensory Enhancement (PSE), a Neurologic Music Therapy method, has shown benefits for upper extremity (UE) rehabilitation. In PSE, movement components are translated into musical patterns to provide temporal, spatial, and force motor cues. Auditory-motor network coupling is one neural mechanism underlying PSE. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) in stroke may speed up motor recovery by rebalancing damaged interhemispheric networks. This study aims to determine benefits of pairing tDCS and PSE for stroke rehabilitation to optimize functional outcomes using applied auditory science and non-invasive brain stimulation. Methods: Eligibility includes adults with arm hemiparesis due to chronic stroke. Exclusions include severe cognitive deficits, apraxia, neglect; neurodegenerative or psychiatric disease; and contraindications for tDCS. A randomized, sham-controlled treatment design was used whereby participants receive 20 minutes of 1mA anodal, bilateral tDCS stimulation to M1 during six PSE sessions. Pre/post-test and retention are assessed using BBT, WMFT, FM and motion captured kinematics. Results: Preliminary results [N=10] show significant behavioral improvements in chronic stroke [M=5.1 yrs. post]. Similar increases were found for both the paired tDCS/PSE and sham-tDCS/PSE protocols. This is consistent with findings by Cordes et al., [2024]. Selected kinematic analysis shows improvements in velocity and acceleration at the wrist joint confirming findings by Loria et al., [2022]. This study is still underway and complete results will be available at conference presentation. Conclusions: PSE shows potential benefits to motor recovery in chronic stroke. Combined applications of tDCS to optimize UE recovery may require further investigation regarding stimulation location, intensity, and frequency.
