N2  - Background: People with cystic fibrosis (PwCF) treated with elexacaftor/ tezacaftor/ivacaftor (ETI) have reported development of neuropsychiatric adverse effects, including poor mood and cognition, mental fogginess, anxiety and depression, insomnia, and suicidality [1], which in some cases resolved or improved upon discontinuation of ETI [2]. Thus, there is a critical need to understand the biological mechanisms underlying neuropsychiatric symptoms. Because ETI crosses the blood-brain barrier [1, 3, 4], we hypothesize that it impairs central nervous system function; in particular, we propose that it disrupts neurotransmitter responses and synaptic plasticity in the hippocampus. Some of the neuropsychiatric disorders reported after ETI treatment, such as insomnia and depression, are linked to impaired hippocampal function [5–7]. Methods: To test our hypothesis, we used the hippocampi of humanized mice expressing WT CFTR and homozygous for the ΔF508 mutation. We exposed cultured hippocampal neurons to ETI for 48 hours (3 mM elexacaftor and ivacaftor, 1 mM tezacaftor). We then used patch-clamp electrophysiology to study alterations in neuronal electrical signal transmission in response to excitatory (AMPA and NMDA) and inhibitory (GABA) responses. Results: ETI altered the neuronal function in the hippocampus, reducing AMPA-evoked electrical currents in the hippocampi of mice. Furthermore, inhibitory GABA-evoked electrical currents showed a positive shift in their reversal potential, demonstrating impaired chloride homeostasis. In contrast, NMDA-evoked currents were unaffected by the treatment. Conclusions: These findings provide insight into ETI's effects on the central nervous system and a possible mechanism for the medication's neuropsychiatric side effects. ETI alters the function of key ionic receptors involved in synaptic transmission and plasticity, which is consistent with hippocampal dysfunction in rodent insomnia and depression syndromes. Our findings highlight the importance of studying the effect of ETI therapy on the nervous system, which expresses high levels of CFTR. Acknowledgements: Canadian Institutes of Health Research; NSERC discovery; CFF.AM. References [1] Neuropsychiatric adverse effects from CFTR modulators deserve a serious research effort. Curr Opin Pulm Med 2023;29(6):603–9. doi: 10. 1097/MCP.0000000000001014. [2] Tindell W, Su A, Oros SM, Rayapati AO, Rakesh G. Trikafta and psychopathology in cystic fibrosis: a case report. Psychosomatics 2020;61(6):735–8. [3] Gavioli EM, Guardado N, Haniff F, Deiab N, Vider E. A current review of the safety of cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator modulators. J Clin Pharm Ther 2021;46(2):286–94. [4] Qiu F, Habgood M, Schneider-Futschik EK. The balance between the safety of mother, fetus, and newborn undergoing cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator treatments during pregnancy. ACS Pharmacol Transl Sci 2020;3(5):835–43. [5] Tartt AN, Mariani MB, Hen R, Mann JJ, Boldrini M. Dysregulation of adult hippocampal neuroplasticity in major depression: pathogenesis and therapeutic implications. Mol Psychiatry 2022;27(6):2689–99. doi: 10.1038/s41380-022-01520-y. [6] Han S, Li X-X,Wei S, Zhao D, Ding J, Xu Y, et al. Orbitofrontal cortexhippocampus potentiation mediates relief for depression: A randomized double-blind trial and TMS-EEG study. Cell Rep Med 2023;4 (6):101060. doi: 10.1016/j.xcrm.2023.101060. [7] Idunkova A, Lacinova L, Dubiel-Hoppanova L. Stress, depression, and hippocampus: from biochemistry to electrophysiology. Gen Physiol Biophys 2023;42(2):107–22. doi: 10.4149/gpb_2023001.
