N2  - Introduction: The tau tracer [18F]MK-6240 exhibits strong affinity and specificity for hyperphosphorylated tau, a key biomarker in Alzheimer's Disease (AD). However, several studies have highlighted the existence of off-target signals from extracerebral structures, particularly in the meninges. These structures, being close to the cortical ribbon, could interfere with important target areas and the gray cerebellum, often used as a reference region. In this study, we report our progress for disentangling the tau-specific, and off-target bindings of the [18F]MK-6240 PET signal by employing non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) at the level of individual brain regions. Methods: NMF is a technique used in dynamic PET data analysis to identify key components from spatiotemporal signal variations within a sequence. In this context, [18F]MK-6240 dynamic PET data can be represented by a matrix V of size N×M, where N is the number of voxels in each 3D volume, and M is the number of time frames. NMF assumes that the dynamic PET data can be approximated by a linear combination of a predefined small number of ki products, the factor images W of size N x ki and factor curves H of size ki x M such that V≈WH. The matrix W contains the spatial representation of each component, while H contains the corresponding time activity curves (TACs) for each component. NMF minimizes the objective function (1); here using Kullback-Leibler divergence (D). We utilized the Multiplicative Update (MU) rule to minimize divergence between V and WH, ensuring nonnegativity. Since a good initialization is crucial to guide the optimization process toward a physiologically plausible solution, we initialized factor curves H with representative TACs and factor images W using probabilistic white and grey matter masks. The factor image for potential off-target signals had random initial values. Our analysis advanced by adopting a region-of-interest (ROI) approach, based on FreeSurfer brain parcellation. By applying NMF to individual ROIs, we can more accurately account for regional heterogeneity in tracer uptake, enhancing our ability to distinguish off-target binding within discrete anatomical structures. In the optimization, we used a weighting matrix based on time frames, giving more emphasis to later, longer-duration frames for their richer steady-state tracer information. NMF was applied to 120-min PET dynamic images from a cognitively normal subject with extra-cerebral signals and an AD patient with both specific and extra-cerebral signals. Results: The application of NMF on [18F]MK-6240 dynamic PET imaging successfully differentiated three distinct components. In cognitively normal subject (Figure 1A), the first component (F1) essentially represented free [18F]MK-6240 within the brain tissue, with the corresponding factor images mirroring cerebral perfusion maps. The second component (F2) was effective in isolating the off-target signals primarily originating from extracerebral areas. The third component (F3) was characterized by a pattern indicative of non-specific binding, with a pronounced presence in the white matter regions. In contrast, for subjects with Alzheimer's Disease (AD) (Figure 1B), NMF permitted the isolation of the specific tau-related signal within the third component (F3), while the non-specific signal appeared to sum with the free signal, leaving the off-target signal isolated. Conclusions: The refinements introduced in our methodology have enhanced the differentiation of off-target signals from other signal components in [18F]MK-6240 PET imaging. The strategic integration of a meticulous initialization process, the incorporation of time frame weighting, and the adoption of a region-of-interest (ROI) by ROI strategy have significantly bolstered both the precision and physiological pertinence of our analysis. Future work will be directed towards corroborating our results across larger and more diverse patient populations.
