N2  - Background: It is estimated that more than half of all people living with multiple sclerosis (MS) are currently using cannabis products, and up to 20% will likely develop cannabis use disorder (CUD). While there is growing evidence of benefit for stopping cannabis use, particularly for common symptoms of cognitive dysfunction or depression, there are few, if any, accessible options for intervention. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) can be used to target the neural circuitry of the addiction cycle, offering a promising treatment for substance use disorder. Objectives: To evaluate the feasibility of a remotely supervised home-based intervention using tDCS paired with mindfulness meditation for people with MS and CUD. Methods: In this all-remote nationally-enrolling pilot shamcontrolled trial, we recruited women with relapsing-remitting MS seeking to reduce their cannabis use. Eligible participants were required to meet CUD criteria without having other substance use disorders, psychiatric conditions, or psychiatric distress (Kessler Psychological Distress Scale (K10)). Once enrolled, participants were shipped study kits containing a laptop computer for enabling live supervision, and a tDCS device programmed for their double-blinded active vs. sham condition. Participants completed an intervention of dorsolateral prefrontal cortex tDCS for 20 sessions (2.0 mA; anode over F3, cathode over F4; 20 minutes) paired with audio guided mindfulness tracks («10 Minute Mind»). Results: This ongoing trial has enrolled n=42 participants with a mean age of 43.0±10.7 years, 45% White, 33% Black or African American; 29% Hispanic/Latino. The sample has a median disease duration: 9.6±7.8 years and median Patient Determined Disease Steps (PDDS) score of 3.0. All participants confirmed cannabis use with a single panel urine drug screen and reported mild/moderate distress (20.8±7.6). The majority of the sample (66%) began using cannabis products (75% inhaling or smoking, 17% edibles, 9% other method of ingestion) after their MS diagnosis, with an average use duration of 11.6±9.2 years and the most common ingestion method being joints (31.4%) followed by hand pipes (17.1%). There has been an 88% retention rate and among the n=34 who completed the intervention thus far, 85% successfully finished 15/20 sessions, with an average of 19.7±3.2 sessions completed. Conclusions: Cannabis use disorder is a growing problem for many people living with MS. A one-month all-remote intervention of tDCS combined with mindfulness meditation may provide an option for accessible and effective intervention to support reduced or discontinued cannabis use.
