N2  - Background: Clinically, the incidence of perioperative neurocognitive disorders (PND) is high due to the lack of effective treatment Method. Even worse, delaying treatment after the onset of cognitive impairment can cause patients to miss the best opportunities for prevention and treatment. Therefore, it is important to explore the preventive treatment Method of PND. Our objective was to explore the effects of prophylactic high-frequency repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation(rTMS)on PND in elderly mice and preliminarily identify its mechanism. Methods: Twenty-four 18-month-old mice were randomly divided into control group, operation group and rTMS group. Mice in the control group did not undergo anesthesia and operation, and mice in the operation group and rTMS group underwent experimental laparotomy under anesthesia. 10 days before surgery, mice in control group and operation group received rTMS sham stimulation, and mice in rTMS group received 5 Hz high frequency rTMS stimulation until the end of the experiment. The motor ability and anxiety of each group were evaluated by open field test on the 3rd day after surgery, and the cognitive function of each group was evaluated by Y maze test on the 4th day after surgery. After Y maze test, the protein expression levels of BDNF, TrkB and NGF in the hippocampal tissues of mice in each group were detected by western blotting. Results: Our Result showed no differences in motor ability and anxious behavior among the groups, as indicated by the time the mice spent in the central area, the total distance traveled, and the average speed of movement in the open-field test (p > 0.05). Y-maze test showed that compared with control mice, the length of stay in the new arm and the distance of exploring the new arm decreased significantly in the operation group (p < 0.05); When compared with the surgery group, high-frequency rTMS treated mice showed improvement in cognitive function, as indicated by a significant increase in the time spent in the new arm and the distance explored by the rTMS group mice (p < 0.05). Western blotting revealed that compared with the control group, the relative expressions of BDNF, TrkB and NGF proteins in the hippocampal tissue of mice in the operation group were significantly decreased (p < 0.05); While compared with the operation group, the relative expressions of BDNF, TrkB and NGF proteins in the hippocampal tissue of mice in rTMS group were significantly increased (p < 0.05). Conclusions: This study demonstrated that prophylactic high-frequency rTMS improved perioperative neurocognitive disorders in elderly mice by promoting the expression of BDNF, TrkB and NGF proteins in the hippocampus.
