N2  - Background: Schizophrenia spectrum disorders (SSDs) often feature social cognitive impairments, which are debilitating and lack treatment options. This feasibility study examined the effect of individually-targeted repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) to the dorsomedial prefrontal cortex (DMPFC) on social cognitive network functional connectivity (i.e., mentalizing and simulation networks) in individuals with SSDs. Methods: We conducted a two-week, double-blind, randomized clinical trial comparing 10Hz rTMS and intermittent theta burst stimulation (iTBS) to sham stimulation of the DMPFC in adults with SSDs. Participants completed pre- and post-treatment magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), including a social processing task. Neurostimulation was individually targeted using electric field and functional connectivity mapping. Within-mentalizing and between mentalizing-simulation network functional connectivity metrics were calculated pre- and post-rTMS. Effect sizes were used to compare the magnitude of changes after 10Hz rTMS and iTBS versus sham. Results: Analyses included 43 participants (10Hz rTMS N=15, iTBS N=15, sham N=13) following quality control. There was a greater increase in mentalizing network connectivity following iTBS (d=0.53), but not 10Hz rTMS (d=0.07), versus sham. Little change was seen in mentalizing-simulation connectivity when comparing iTBS and 10Hz rTMS to sham. Pain scores were low in all groups (means < 5) and drop-out rates did not differ across groups. Conclusions: This study marks the first investigation of rTMS effects on social cognitive circuitry in SSDs, incorporating individualized targeting approaches. Our results suggest that iTBS can change mentalizing network connectivity with medium effect size. We are now embarking on a larger clinical trial using iTBS versus sham to assess changes in social cognitive performance. Funding Source: National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH); Brain and Behavior Research Foundation (BBRF) Keywords: Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS), Schizophrenia Spectrum Disorders, Functional connectivity, Social Cognition
