N2  - Background and aims: Stroke is a major cause of mortality and morbidity globally, with post-stroke cognitive impairment (PSCI) affecting up to half of stroke patients. Although pharmacological and non-pharmacological interventions are available, there is a lack of definitive effective treatments for PSCI. Non-invasive brain stimulation (NIBS), such as intermittent theta burst stimulation (iTBS), has emerged as a promising therapy. This systematic review aims to determine the efficacy of iTBS as a treatment for PSCI. Methods: Searching PubMed, Web of science, Scopus, Cochrane Library and CNKI for relevant words and terms from database creation to 1 April 2023, relevant randomized controlled trials that met our inclusion criteria were included. The risk of bias was assessed using the Cochrane Risk Assessment tool. Meta analysis of data was conducted using Review Manager version 5.4.1. Results: A total of 6 studies involving 349 post-stroke cognitive impairment patients were included in the study. Meta analysis showed that iTBS significantly improved Global cognition measured by Mini-Mental Status Examination (MMSE) Score, Repeatable Battery for the Assessment of Neuropsychological Status (RBANS scores), or the Lowenstein Occupational Therapy Cognitive Assessment scale (LOTCA) (Std. Mean Difference = 1.12 95 % CI = [0.59–1.65], P < 0.0001). iTBS also had significant positive effects on Attention, Activities of daily life, visou-spatial perception and orientation. No serious adverse effects were reported in included studies. [Formula presented] Conclusions: The current study suggests that iTBS is a safe and efficient non-invasive treatment that can enhance the cognitive abilities and daily living skills of patients with post-stroke cognitive impairment.
