N2  - Background and aims: Dementia causes progressive cognitive decline. Eventually, patients become entirely dependent on others. Unfortunately, existing pharmacological treatments demonstrates limited efficacy. Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS), a non-invasive, electrodeless, focal brain stimulation technique, has heterogenous effects on dementia. Thus, an optimal protocol should be evaluated through a bio-marker, such as Clusterin (CLU) that directly correlates with rate of clinical progression. Dementia resilience is remarkably high in high-landers. The understanding of highlander genetic expression could lead to the discovery of a novel therapy. Finally, we hypothesize that multisession rTMS protocol will prevent dementia progression by delaying apoptosis regardless of demographics. Methods: Inclusion & exclusion criteria of dementia: Must have: • Diagnosed with cognitive impairment or dementia • Ability to obtain a motor threshold, determined during the screening process • Stable condition and living environment to enable attendance at scheduled clinic visits • Willing to remain on stable regimen during the treatment phase • Able to read and verbalize understanding Must not have: • Prior exposure to rTMS or electroconvulsive therapy • Cardiac pacemaker, cochlear implant, or other implanted device or metal in the brain • Current or prior history of seizure disorder • Traumatic brain injury within the last 2 months • Participation in interventional clinical trial at the same time as this trial • Known current psychosis • History of mass lesion or cerebral infarct • Not fluent in Hindi/ English or hearing impairment severe enough to impair comprehension Results: [Formula presented] This being protocol. Results not applicable Conclusions: [Formula presented] This being a protocol. Conclusions not applicable
