N2  - Background and aims: To first establish the effectiveness and safety of projective connection-based transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) and explore potential neuroimaging mechanism in older adults with amnestic mild cognitive impairment (aMCI). Methods: Forty-two outpatients 50–80 years with a diagnosis of aMCI and 21 age- and education-matched healthy controls (HCs) were included in the randomized two-arm, clinical trial with open treatment and blinded assessors. After tracking the “cortex-hippocampus” network with white matter fiber connection in the 21 HCs and identifying stimulation target (symptom-related functional connections [FC]) in the 42 outpatients, the 42 outpatients were randomly assigned in a 1:1 ratio to receive a course of 2 weeks of either projective connection-based TMS or sham stimulation. The primary outcome measure was change from baseline in auditory verbal learning test, long-term delayed recall scale (Delta AVLT_N5). Results: A total of 21 patients were randomized to projective connection-based TMS and 21 to sham stimulation, of whom 42 (100%) were assessed for the primary outcome, respectively, whereas safety was assessed in all randomized patients. Mean (SD) AVLT_N5 score improved from 2.43 (1.43) to 5.29 (1.98) for projective connection-based TMS and 2.52 (1.44) to 3.86 (2.39) for sham stimulation (adjusted difference, 1.52; 95% confidence interval [CI], 0.54 to 2.51; p = 0.003; Cohen's d = 0.97). A significant correlation was identified between the delta FC value and delta AVLT_N5 in the projective connection-based TMS group. Conclusions: In older adults with aMCI, projective connection-based TMS improves long-term delayed recall, which may mark effect by down-regulating FC value between left hippocampus and left precuneus.
