N2  - The 2020 report of the Lancet Commission on dementia prevention, intervention, and care stated that the age-related incidence of dementia has decreased due to the improvements of potentially modifiable risk factors. Based on the neuroscientific evidence, we have developed a multimodal brain empowerment approach which encompassed a systematic physical resistance exercise with RAGT, music therapy, computerized cognitive therapy, tDCS, light therapy and core breathing exercises. Hence, the present experimental research aimed to determine the immediate effectiveness of the multimodal brain empowerment approach on EEG patterns and effectiveness questionnaires and to ascertain underpinning neural mechanism between the two different multimodal or combination of the therapies (a combination of tDCS, light therapy and computerized cognitive therapy (TLC) and RAGT, music therapy, core exercise (REM)) in both young healthy adults and older adults with high risk of MCI. The basic premise is that both combinations would have similar effects on EEG patterns in both young healthy adults and older adults with high risk of MCI. Forty participants, twenty older adults with MCI, twenty young adults were recruited. All participants underwent the EEG measurement to assess intervention related changes in neuroplasticity during the Brain-Fit intervention. The Brain-Fit intervention involved six different interventions and two combinations, which were administered randomly. This clinical research study demonstrated both the young and old groups showed a decrease in delta waves during TLC and REM, along with an increase in theta, alpha, and beta waves. The topographic maps also revealed significant event-related desynchronization (ERD) in the frontal, temporal, parietal, and occipital lobes of the brain during both TLC and REM. These findings offer clinical evidence-based insights into the use of TLC and REM, which can not only enhance cognitive function but also activate the entire brain, in both young adults and individuals with MCI. Declaration of Interest Statement: This study was supported by the “Brain Korea 21 PLUS Project (Grant No. 2021-51-0151)”, the Korean Research Foundation for Department of Physical Therapy in the Graduate School of Yonsei University.
