N2  - Background: Transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) is a potentially effective and safer treatment strategy for cognitive impairment. However, evidence of TMS efficacy on cognition in psychiatric disorders like depression, schizophrenia, and bipolar disorders is limited. We aimed to review the existing literature on the effects of r-TMS on cognition in psychiatric conditions. Methods: A comprehensive search of several databases (Medline, Embase, Cochrane, APA PsycINFO, Web of Science, and Scopus) from 2000 to January 2022 was conducted. The primary outcome measure for this review was any cognitive changes. rTMS treatment parameters were also collected. This review part is registered with PROSPERO, CRD42022326423. Results: We identified 22 articles encompassing 14 randomized controlled trials (RCT), 6 open-label prospective, and 2 open-label retrospective studies. The total sample size is 1177, with 384 (38.4%) females, and a mean age range of 41- 47 years. The majority of RCTs were on schizophrenia (8) followed by unipolar depression (4) and bipolar depression (2). TMS protocols used high frequency (> 5Hz) and 1000-2000 total pulses per session. Left DLPFC is used as a stimulation site. There was heterogeneity in the studies. There was demonstrated cognitive improvement with rTMS in 4 of 6 (67%) RCTs for major depression, 3 of 8 (38%) RCTs for schizophrenia, and 5 of 8 (63%) open-label studies for major depression. Conclusions: From these reviewed articles, there is evidence of improved cognitive functions with rTMS depression, schizophrenia, and other psychiatric conditions. Further studies are needed to determine optimal TMS protocols in psychiatric populations with comorbid cognitive impairment. Conflicts of Interests: Dr. Croarkin has received research support from the National Institute of Mental Health, Magventure, Neuronetics, NeoSync, and Pfizer. He has received material support from and provided consultation to Myriad Neuroscience. He has consulted for Procter & Gamble Company. Funding: Mayo Clinic CCATS Grant Number UL1 TR002377, internal small grant funds to Dr. Pagali and Dr. Lapid. Dr. Lapid also receives NIH funding for research. Disclosures: None
