N2  - Objectives: Primary goal of this randomized controlled trial was to see if the intensified transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) protocol could improve visual cognition in patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) both immediately and long-term. Secondary goal was to study neural underpinnings of the behavioral effect using fMRI. Content: Five days intensified anodal tDCS was applied over the left DLPFC (cathode: contralateral orbitofrontal cortex) using 2mA in two 20-minute trains separated by a 20-minute pause on 14 real and 16 sham MCI subjects. Prior to, right after and one month after the stimulation, participants performed a visual object matching task in fMRI – offline task and a visual working memory task was performed during each stimulation session – online task. Behavioral outcomes (both offline and online tasks) and fMRI task activations were analyzed using t-tests, along with linear mixed model analysis. In offline task there was a trend towards improving performance in the real stimulation group (F = 2541, p = 0.088), in online task we found statistically significant differences in both accuracy and reaction times (p ≤ 0.001) favoring real over sham stimulation group. We observed a statistically significant fMRI task activation in right putamen/insula cluster (p < 0.05 with FWE correction at the cluster level) that correlated with our behavioral outcomes. Unfortunately, we could not find statistically significant improvement (only a trend) after tDCS on visual cognition in our offline task possibly due to small sample size. But we found significant online effects of the tDCS and fMRI task activation that correlated with our behavioral outcomes. Keywords: tDCS; Mild cognitive impairment; fMRI; Cognitive functions; Visual cognition; Neuromodulation.
