N2  - Objectives: Explore baseline differences in working memory (WM) between healthy and cognitively impaired elderly people. Study the efficacy of combined transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) in the theta-gamma range and computerized cognitive training (CCT) on WM performance in the elderly. Content: With the increasing number of elderly people, the incidence of neurodegenerative diseases such as “mild cognitive impairment (MCI)” or “Alzheimer's disease (AD)” has increased significantly in recent decades. One of the most problematic impairments affecting these patients relates to the deterioration of WM. Since pharmacological treatment options in this population are limited, appropriate alternative treatment strategies are being explored which may improve or preserve WM in healthy and cognitively impaired elderly people. In this triple-blinded placebo-controlled randomized clinical trial 76 elderly subjects aged 55–85 years received a combination of either active or sham theta-gamma cross-frequency tACS and CCT, over a period of 6 weeks. In a total of 16 sessions, subjects underwent a 20-minute bilateral stimulation of the Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex (DLPFC) while simultaneously performing tablet-based n-back training. To classify subjects as healthy or cognitively impaired, the Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) was administered at baseline. Although a final analysis is still pending due to ongoing data collection, interim analyses already support our hypothesis by showing the efficacy of CCT to improve WM with a tendency for active DLPFC stimulation to magnify this effect. Keywords: Non-invasive brain stimulation; NIBS; Transcranial electrical stimulation; tES; Transcranial alternating current stimulation; tACS; Cognitive training; Aging; Mild cognitive impairment; MCI; Neurodegenerative diseases.
