N2  - Introduction: The prevalence of Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) is increasing as is the tremendous patient and caregiver burden. Existing medications provide only partial symptomatic benefits and non-pharmacological treatment approaches are needed. Non-invasive neuromodulation method, transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS), applied in studies involving brief treatment protocols have shown promising potential for AD. However, knowledge gaps remain regarding the long-term benefits. To address these gaps, we are conducting a large (N=100) randomized clinical trial of 6 months of at-home tDCS to determine effects on cognitive performance, mood, quality of life, and changes in functional and structural brain connectivity/network, and to explore durability of the effects in a 9-month period. Here, we report on the development, implementation, and day-to-day logistics of the at-home tDCS protocol, including an enhanced remote monitoring procedure (ERMP) that we have developed to ascertain comprehensive remote monitoring for safety and protocol adherence. Methods: Participants are age ≥60 years, diagnosed with mild-to-moderate stage AD; able to provide informed consent. Participation of informal caregivers is optional. Active tDCS at the intensity of 2mA or sham is applied with two electrodes clipped to a headband over the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, for 30 minutes, 5 days/week for 26 weeks at home, using a device with built-in dose control, paired with a tablet allowing for a video-connection. Results: The protocol includes 6 study visits: V1 (consent, screening), V2 (baseline, tDCS training), V3 (refresh training and first tDCS application under supervision of study personnel), V4 (end of 6-month tDCS intervention, outcome assessment), V5-6 (post-intervention follow-up at 7 and 9 months). The at-home tDCS is remotely supervised using video, phone and the ERMP that includes photos of the participants’ forehead at three time-points during sessions: a) Prior to the placement of the headgear, b) after placement of the headgear prior to tDCS, and c) after tDCS is completed and the headgear has been removed. The ERMP assists with evaluation of skin condition in a single session (pre- and post-stimulation), as well as long-term, and allows for quality check of electrode placement. To date, 54 participants have been consented and screened; of those, 26 were eligible, randomized and successfully trained to apply the at-home tDCS protocol with the ERMP procedure. Conclusion: This is the first trial applying a long-term at-home tDCS protocol with post-intervention follow-up and a unique ERMP that represents an elevated system of safety and adherence monitoring suitable for patients with mild-to-moderate AD. Disclosure: Jordan Van Zyl, BS: None, Christine Kim, MSEd: None, Lela Seekwar, BS: None, Kevin Ha, BS: None, Carmen Urizar, BA: None, Mairim Melecio-Vazquez, MS: None, Emmeline Ayers, MPH: None, Erica Weiss, PhD: Sonde Health: Contracted Research:, Jessica Zwerling, MD: None, Helena Blumen, PhD, MS: None, Russell Portenoy, MD: None, Joe Verghese, MBBS, MS, FRCPI: None, Helena Knotkova, PHD: Soterix Medical, Inc: Principal Investigator: Self, Ybrain, Inc: Principal Investigator: Self, Ybrain, Inc: Speaker/Teacher: Self
