N2  - Background: Cognitive control deficits are a defining characteristic and diagnostic criteria of alcohol use disorder (AUD) and Alzheimer's disease (AD). One mechanism through which transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) may improve cognition is through enhancement of BDNF signaling. Lower circulating BDNF has been linked to increased risk of AUD, while administration of a TrkB agonist similar to BDNF decreases overall drinking behavior. Similarly, AD is characterized by a loss in BDNF. Therefore, this experiment aimed to evaluate the efficacy of frontal TMS treatment in increasing cortical BDNF expression in the 3xTgAD mouse model of AD -a well-established model wherein BDNF is reduced at baseline. Ongoing studies aim to translate this approach to AUD. Methods: Twenty-four female 3xTgAD mice were outfitted with a cranial coil support fixed over Bregma. Animals were randomized to receive active or sham 10 Hz rTMS daily for 14 days. Following treatment, mice underwent a battery of cognitive tasks. Post-mortem brain tissue from the temporal cortex was assayed for BDNF gene expression via qPCR. The hippocampus was homogenized and assayed via Western blot for BDNF and TrkB protein. The same set of experiments were run on B6 mice (n = 28) for quantitative comparisons. Results: Naïve, sham, and stimulated 3xTgAD mice developed both plaques and tangles throughout the brain. TMS had no effect on plaque or tangle load (p > 0.1). Animals who received active TMS showed an improvement in the object-place task (p < 0.05) and BDNF upregulation (p < 0.05). BDNF protein levels in the hippocampus showed a trend towards improvement (p < 0.1), while TrkB levels were significantly increased following active TMS (p < 0.05). TMS had little effect on B6 mice across measures, suggesting TMS may normalize BDNF loss rather than generally increasing BDNF. Estrus cycling had no effect on variables measured (all p's > 0.1). Conclusions: These data demonstrate TMS may enhance BDNF expression and rescue cognitive loss, and thus is a promising avenue for AUD treatment. Reduced BDNF expression following prolonged alcohol consumption likely contributes to cognitive control deficits commonly observed among individuals with AUD. Results from an ongoing, pilot trial (n = 72 C57BL/J6 mice) to assess TMS-induced changes in BDNF expression and subsequent alcohol consumption will be discussed.
