N2  - Background: In participants with Major Depressive Disorder (MDD), a N-Methyl-D-Aspartate (NMDA) partial agonist D-Cycloserine, paired with intermittent theta-burst stimulation (iTBS) delivered to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) results in greater symptom improvements than iTBS+placebo. The presumed mechanism is enhanced NMDA receptor dependent plasticity in the DLPFC. We aimed to determine whether this treatment combination improved subjective and objective cognitive function. Methods: Fifty participants with MDD were enrolled in a double-blind randomized placebo-controlled trial in which participants received either daily iTBS+Placebo or iTBS+D-Cycloserine (100mg) for two weeks, followed by 2 weeks of stimulation without an adjuvant. The THINC-integrated tool was used to measure subjective and objective cognitive function at baseline and at 2 weeks, and depression severity was measured with the Montgomery Asberg Depression Rating Scale (MADRS). Improvements in cognitive function were investigated using repeated measures ANOVA and this was repeated as an ANCOVA to account for MADRS change. Results: The iTBS+D-Cycloserine group showed significant improvements on the Perceived Deficits Questionnaire (subjective measure of cognitive function) and the ‘One Back’ working memory measure (both p<0.05). Repeating the analysis, covarying for MADRS change, the subjective improvements did not withstand correction for depressive symptom improvement, however, the working memory improvements did (F(1,39)=5.41, p=0.025). Conclusions: Our data suggests improvements in subjective cognitive function and working memory performance in MDD following treatment with D-Cycloserine+iTBS. Improvement in working memory, a heavily DLPFC dependent task, is not attributable to improvement in depressive symptoms. This suggests functional remodelling of the DLPFC by facilitating NMDA receptor dependent synaptic plasticity. Funding Source: Brain and Behavior Research Fund; Campus Alberta Innovates Keywords: Cognitive Deficits, Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS), Intermittent Theta-Burst Stimulation (iTBS), Randomized Clinical Trial, Major Depressive Disorder (MDD)
