N2  - Background: Working memory deficits are prevalent in neuropsychiatric disorders. New treatments aim for synergistic effects of cognitive trainings and non-invasive brain stimulation. The present study is exploring the effects of fronto-parietal theta tACS on a working memory training. We also investigate near transfer to verbal working memory, and EEG functional connectivity. Methods: This was a randomized, sham-controlled, pre-registered trial in a three-arm parallel design in 44 participants (https://osf.io/e5zhc). The study consisted of 6 sessions including pre-training session, three training sessions with concurrent tACS, a post-training session and a 4-week follow-up session. We applied 27 min of 1,5 mA peak-to-peak 5 Hz tACS to the right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (F4) and parietal cortex (P4), either in-phase (O°), anti-phase (180°) or sham. Results: Anti-phase tACS slowed response times during tACS application dependent on baseline response time and session (LMM, β = -0.19, p = .03). There was no difference in achieved task difficulty between tACS conditions. However, RM-ANOVA revealed a more liberal response bias for in-phase tACS, leading to more Hits and more False Alarms with concurrent tACS, all p < .001. The difference score (post-pre) of the weighted phase lag index (wPLI) between the target electrodes F4 and P4 revealed higher functional connectivity for in-phase tACS compared to sham, p = .012. Conclusions: This study shows immediate and lasting phase-specific behavioral and neurophysiological effects of 5 Hz tACS combined with cognitive training. The combination of tACS and cognitive training paradigms thus represents a promising approach to improve cognitive deficits across the neuropsychiatric spectrum. Keywords: Noninvasive brain stimulation, Transcranial alternating current stimulation, Visuospatial Working Memory, Theta oscillations, Functional connectivity
