N2  - Background: Clinical trials that have targeted the well-known pathogenic mechanisms of Alzheimer's disease (AD) have failed to identify effective interventions to treat or reverse the disease. Recently, a series of studies have indicated that driving gamma neuronal activity has a remarkable effect on reducing AD pathology and improving patients' cognitive function. Objectives: The primary purpose of this study was to determine whether 40 Hz brain stimulation, through Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS), is effective in improving cognitive function in amnestic Mild Cognitive Impairment (aMCI) and AD patients. Method: A single case, randomized multiple baseline design, across 8 participants was implemented. Patients with diagnosis of aMCI and Probable AD, received daily TMS treatment therapy sessions for 2 weeks (10 sessions in total). Each session included 25 trains consisting of 1 second of 40 Hz (40 pulses per train) with 29 seconds inter-train interval. Each patient received 1000 pulses per session, at 90% of their resting motor threshold over the left and the right precuneus (1 site each day). Results: A strict adherence in study's protocol resulted in a mean reduction of 5.75 points on the Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale-cognitive subscale and an improvement on Mini Mental State Examination, as evaluated through the Wilcoxon signed-rank test (P < .05). The Percentage of Data Exceeding the Median (REM) effect size index, indicated a moderate treatment effectiveness on AD patients' performance (n = 5) in the Trail Making Test A (TMT; REM = 0.83). A highly effective response (REM = 0.9) was observed on the aMCI patients (n = 2) on the TMT A and B and on the naming task. In one of the aMCI subjects a moderate effect (REM = 0.7) was observed also on the delayed recall. Conclusions: TMS brain stimulation at 40 Hz is a feasible and safe intervention that shows the potential to alleviate AD related cognitive symptoms, especially during the MCI stage.
