N2  - According to forecasts, 22% of the world’s population will be over 60 years old by 2050, compared with only 11% in 2013. This is and will be accompanied by an increasing prevalence of cognitive diseases, which mostly occur at a higher age. As a precursor to dementia, so-called “mild cognitive impairment (MCI)” represents a critical intermediate state. The memory performance of MCI patients often declines drastically; about half of them develop dementia in the following three years. In addition to diagnosing MCI as early as possible, appropriate treatment options are needed. The aim of our study was to explore the effects of a combination therapy of theta-gamma cross-frequency transcranial non-invasive alternating current stimulation (CFC-tACS) and computerized cognitive training (CCT) for the treatment of cognitive impairment, focusing on non-declarative memory. Unlike declarative memory, there is no consensus on whether non-declarative (implicit) memory is impaired in the presence of an MCI diagnosis. Therefore, we examined both the baseline differences in non-declarative memory performance between healthy and cognitively impaired elderly as well as the effects of CFC-tACS and CCT on implicit learning, which has not been explored yet. We conducted a triple-blinded placebo-controlled randomized trial in which 35 subjects older than 55 years were assessed using the Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) and were classified as either cognitively healthy or cognitively impaired. They received a 6-week treatment in which they were stimulated bilaterally at the Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex (DLPFC) for a total of 16 appointments, each for a period of 20 minutes, while undergoing cognitive N-back training. To examine the effects on implicit memory, the Alternating Serial Reaction Time task (ASRT) was applied immediately before and after treatment and three months after treatment to capture both direct and long-term effects. Based on the literature, we hypothesized that the active stimulation of the DLPFC would positively affect implicit memory in the elderly, expecting a larger effect in already cognitively impaired individuals. Preliminary results already show a statistically significant interaction between groups and assessments in terms of ASRT reaction time learning score. This already highlights the potential of tACS combined with CCT to modulate implicit memory.
