N2  - Abstract Background: Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) is a promising intervention for treatment-resistant depression (TRD). Research in Parkinson’s disease has shown that DBS may lead to cognitive impairments. To assess if DBS leads to cognitive impairments in TRD, we investigated the effects of DBS on cognitive functioning in TRD with a meta-analysis. Methods: A systematic search in PubMed was performed. Articles were eligible if standardized neuropsychological tests were used to assess cognitive functioning in patients with TRD who were treated with DBS. Each study had to include a preoperative assessment and a follow-up assessment between 6 to 18 months. Separate meta-analyses were performed for different cognitive domains (verbal and visual memory, executive functioning, verbal fluency, working memory, attention/psychomotor speed, language, and intelligence). Random-effects models were used to compare standardized mean difference (SMD, Hedges’ g) between preoperative and follow-up assessments. Results: Preliminary results (k = 7, Npreoperative=19-192, Nfollow-up=19-174) show small but significant improvements on cognitive functioning in the cognitive domains of verbal memory (Hedges’ g = 0.22, 95%CI = 0.01-0.43, p=0.04), visual memory (Hedges’ g = 0.37, 95%CI = 0.03-0.71, p=0.04), and executive functions (Hedges’ g = 0.37, 95%CI = 0.15-0.59, p=0.001) following 6 to 18 months of DBS. No significant cognitive impairments were found for any of the cognitive domains following 6 to 18 months of DBS treatment. Conclusions: Our meta-analysis did not find cognitive decline following 6 to 18 months of DBS in patients with TRD. On the contrary, our results suggest cognitive improvement following DBS. However, these small positive effects are to be interpreted with caution due to lack of controlled data. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 23. Neuropsychology Keywords: Deep Brain Stimulation, Depression, Cognitive functioning, Neuropsychological
