N2  - Abstract Older adults are typically less well able to focus, shift, or divide their attention. Since attentional control influences higher level cognitive functions, such as prospective memory, their performance in such tasks is also impaired. On the neural level, there is evidence to suggest that the inferior frontal lobe and the superior parietal lobe are active during both attentional control and prospective memory. In this study, we therefore systematically modulated activity in the inferior frontal lobe or the superior parietal lobe to test how this would influence attentional control or prospective memory in healthy older adults. In a double blind, sham-controlled, and parallel group design, we will include n = 105 healthy older volunteers (60-75 years of age). Participants will be randomly assigned to one of seven groups: they will receive either cathodal, anodal, or sham high-definition transcranial direct current stimulation (HD-tDCS) of the left or right inferior frontal, or the right superior parietal lobe for 20 min (1mA). During and after stimulation, the participants will complete attentional control tasks as well as prospective memory tasks. So far, we have included approximately 60% of the sample. Preliminary results indicate that cathodal stimulation (left inferior frontal or right superior parietal lobe) increased prospective memory accuracy. Similarly, cathodal stimulation increased attentional control when modulating right inferior frontal lobe or right superior parietal lobe activity. In contrast, anodal stimulation (left or right inferior frontal lobe) led to faster responses in the prospective memory task. Our findings will provide a better understanding of the role frontal and parietal regions have in attentional control or prospective memory. This may translate to interventions to counteract cognitive decline in old age Research Category and Technology and Methods Basic Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords: Non-invasive brain stimulation, Prospective memory, Cognitive control, Aging
