N2  - Symposium title: Systematic comparisons of non-invasive brain stimulation protocols to promote cognition Symposium description: Non-invasive brain stimulation can improve cognitive functions. It remains unclear which are the optimal stimulation parameters when targeting different cognitive functions in different clinical and healthy populations. Multiple studies have assessed the clinical and neurophysiological effects of different stimulation parameters. However, protocols may still be optimised to improve the results. Therefore, in this symposium, we will review studies that have systematically varied electrode positioning, inhibition or facilitation, stimulation intensities, or that have directly compared different approaches (e.g., conventional vs. high-definition transcranial direct current stimulation; HD-tDCS) to modulate cognitive functions in healthy or in clinical populations. The goal is to give an overview of best possible protocols for different cognitive functions which can be relevant for anyone working in the field of aging or mental disorders in which these functions are impaired. We will start the session with Nadine Schmidt (M.Sc.) who will present data in healthy elderly volunteers. In her study, frontal or parietal regions were stimulated with HD-tDCS (anodal or cathodal at 1mA) to find the optimal protocol for enhancing attentional control. Simone Weller (M.Sc.) will then present a study in which healthy young volunteers received anodal or cathodal tDCS of 1 or 2 mA over the left or right prefrontal cortex to enhance cognitive control. Sven Passman (Ph.D.) will follow to present a study in which healthy young adults received either theta transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) or beta-tACS at frontal or parietal regions to enhance memory functions. Finally, Ali Salehinejad (Ph.D.) will present a study which compared conventional tDCS to HD-tDCS in patients with depression to find the optimal protocol for enhancing executive dysfunction. Abstract Our ability to pursue inner goals or inhibit responses to irrelevant stimuli is referred to as attentional control. Attentional control comprises different cognitive functions including inhibitory control, shifting, or divided attention, all of them being highly relevant for a range of higher cognitive abilities. Older adults often tend to be impaired in several of these functions and consequently in attentional control. Previous studies found that conventional transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) increased attentional control in older adults. However, it exhibits a bidirectional modulation on a relatively broad area of the brain. In contrast, high definition tDCS (HD-tDCS) allows focal stimulation but studies using HD-tDCS in older adults are rare. In addition, these studies did not systematically compare different electrode positions to optimize effects on attentional control. In this ongoing double blind, sham-controlled, and parallel group study, we will systematically modulate activity in three different brain areas with HD-tDCS to assess which of these protocols optimally enhances attentional control. A total of n = 105 healthy older volunteers (60-75 years of age) will be included and randomly assigned to one of seven groups: each participant will receive either cathodal, anodal, or sham HD-tDCS over the left or right inferior frontal gyrus, or the right superior parietal gyrus for 20 min (1mA). During and after stimulation, participants will complete a range of attentional control tasks. So far, we have included n = 58 participants. Preliminary results indicate particularly beneficial effects of right hemispheric – but not left hemispheric - cathodal stimulation. Our findings will provide a better understanding of the role frontal and parietal regions have in attentional control. This may translate to interventions to counteract cognitive decline in old age. Research Category and Technology and Methods Basic Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords: Attentional control, HD-tDCS, Cognitive control, Aging
