N2  - Symposium title: Concurrent TMS-EEG to characterize the course of neurological disorders Symposium description: Promoting personalization of treatment for neurological patients is closely associated with the need of individual prediction of outcome, course of disease and treatment responsiveness. In order to define reliable proxies at the level of individual patients - a critical factor for clinical translation and personalization - there is a strong need for innovative, but easy to apply methods to generate predictive factors (biomarkers) to phenotype the patients. Combining TMS and EEG (TMS-EEG) provides these methodological requirements. In the present symposium, we will provide an introduction into the concurrent application of TMS-EEG and novel analytical approaches as powerful tools to evaluate and better understand neurological disorders. It allows to non-invasively probe in-vivo brain circuits in humans, permitting the assessment of cortical properties such as brain reactivity, evoked and induced oscillatory activity and interregional connectivity. In recent years, TMS-EEG has been used in various neurological disorders, such as stroke, vigilance disorders or dementia, allowing a better characterization of these diseases in regard of underlying pathophysiological mechanisms, outcome, course, and response to treatment. This symposium will provide an up-to-date overview of the emerging field of TMS-EEG in clinical-translational neuroscience and discuss underlying mechanisms, opportunities and challenges for the development from ‘bench to clinical daily life’. In more detail, we will introduce novel analytical approaches and present actual findings achieved in healthy aged subjects, patients suffering from MCI or dementia, stroke or consciousness disorders. These findings will be critically discussed in the light of the current literature and the methodological challenges, summarizing the status of the field and provide an outlook of it. Abstract TMS-EEG coupling has recently gained strong interest in the functional exploration of the healthy and pathological human brain, as a diagnostic and prognostic tool for several psychiatric and neurological diseases. However, several analytical and methodological limitations still need to be addressed in order to unlock its full potential. This talk will focus on the resolution of two of the most important: the intra and inter-individual variability in the brain response evoked by TMS, and the influence of normal ageing in the features extracted from it. Inheriting the classical analysis framework of evoked related potentials in EEG, most of the TMS-EEG studies still rely on group-based component analyses, that may not hold in the individual subject or trial level (Bridwell et al., 2018), especially in the context of neurological disorders. In order to overcome this problem, a new index based on the regression quality of the individual response in the single trials level is proposed, which fully considers the intra and inter patient variability regarding the evoked response dynamics. Such index proved to be efficient in probing several cortical properties such as the cortical excitability or the intracortical inhibitory system activity, and allowed to assess the spatial resolution of TMS-EEG coupling. Another methodological limitation classically encountered in neurological studies is the advanced age of the observed population. If Increasing evidence is pointing towards an overall decrease of cortical excitability with normal ageing (Guerra et al., 2021), further work is needed to understand its impact on TMS-EEG features. Here, we present new results regarding its influence on cortical excitability, intracortical inhibitory system activity and TMS-induced oscillations patterns. Overall, these studies are a further step in the future potential application of TMS-EEG based biomarkers in clinical routine. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: TMS-EEG, neuroplasticity, intracortical inhibition, healthy ageing
