N2  - Abstract Traumatic brain injury (TBI) has a high incidence in our society and often leads to cognitive impairment. The hippocampus, together with multiple other regions of the medial temporal lobe, is a key player involved in important cognitive functions, such as episodic memory or spatial navigation. So far this structure could not be reached and neuromodulated via standard non-invasive brain stimulation techniques, because of the distance from the surface of the brain and the respective depth-focality trade-off. Transcranial electric temporal interference stimulation (tTIS) opens the great opportunity of reaching and modulating this region and determining its impact on brain activity and respective behavior. After first studies targeting the hippocampus in a healthy young population, the goal is to translate this interventional approach from ’bench to beside’ towards clinical populations. As a first step in this direction, we applied tTIS to the hippocampus in 13 TBI patients, who suffered from cognitive impairment, in a randomized, cross-over, sham-controlled, double-blind study. We investigated whether TI stimulation applied in an intermittent theta burst pattern could modulate hippocampal activity during a face-name association task. tTIS did not show effects during the training phase, however changed the performance during the follow-up sessions, 90 minutes and 24 hours after the stimulation. These proof-of-concept results highlight the potential of tTIS for clinical translation in neurological patients. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 5. Other Transcranial Electrical Stimulation (tES) Keywords: Temporal Interference (TI) stimulation, traumatic brain injury (TBI), Cognitive functions – episodic memory, Neuroplasticity
