N2  - Symposium title: Non-invasive brain stimulation treatments for Alzheimer’s disease Symposium description: In this symposium three different brain stimulation modalities as a treatment for Alzheimer's disease will be presented as well as how to predict the response to magnetic treatment at baseline will be presented. 1. We report on a large multi-site double-blind randomized placebo controlled trial investigating the short and long-term efficacy of active rTMS applied to the prefrontal cortex (PFC) with 2-weeks vs 4-weeks of treatment (5 days/week) and compare these to sham rTMS. Results are presented. 2. In early phases of AD, prominent neuropathological changes are mostly distributed to posterior cortical regions of the brain affecting specifically the precuneus (PC), The results of a randomized, sham-controlled, double-blinded trial performed in mild AD patients who had two-weeks of high-frequency PC-rTMS are presented. 3. Recent literature has highlighted gamma desynchronization as an early occurrence in the pathophysiology of Alzheimer’s disease (AD). In this randomized, double-blind, sham controlled, crossover study, 60 patients were examined pre and post 60 minutes of treatment with gamma-tACS targeting the precuneus. Results are presented. 4. At baseline, to date, there are up to now no means of predicting at baseline the rTMS treatment response of a patient. Using two Electrovestibulography (EVestG) biomarkers extracted from baseline data, a blind test accuracy of 75% using a Leave-one-out-cross-validated linear-discriminant-analysis was achieved for predicting responders versus non-responders. Results are presented. Abstract Recent trials of repetitive transcranial stimulation (rTMS) have reported encouraging results for improving or stabilizing cognition in patients diagnosed with Alzheimer’s disease (AD). However, conclusions about the clinical utility of rTMS treatment have been hampered by small samples, lack of dose investigation, and the wide variation in treatment protocols studied to date. We report on a large multi-site double-blind randomized controlled trial investigating the short and long-term efficacy of active rTMS in two doses of 2-weeks vs 4-weeks of treatment (5 days/week) compared to sham TMS. Participants had a primary diagnosis of AD and a Clinical Dementia Rating (CDR) of 1 or 2. Randomization to treatment group was stratified on age, sex and CDR. Neuro-navigation was used to target rTMS (20 Hz, 30 pulses/train, 25 trains, 10-s intertrain interval) over the left and then the right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex. The primary outcome measure was the Alzheimer Disease Assessment Scale-Cognitive Subscale (ADAS-Cog); we compared its score changes from pre- to post-treatment., with assessments at baseline, after 2 and 4 weeks of intervention, and at 8, 16 and 24 weeks post-treatment. With an initial target sample size of 208 participants, an interim analysis of data from 142 patients (64 women) who have completed the study was conducted. The logarithm of the mean total ADAS-Cog score at baseline did not differ between any of the two doses of active treatment groups and sham group; this trend was the same across the three sites. The change from baseline ADAS-Cog score did not differ significantly between the groups at any time point. The results of this interim analysis do not support the continued use of this neurostimulation protocol for treatment of cognitive impairment in mild to moderate Alzheimer's dementia. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: Alzheimer's disease, rTMS treatment, randomized clinical trial, treatment dose
