N2  - Abstract Background: Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) refers to circumscribed cognitive impairment with intact activities of daily living. MCI has a high rate of progression to dementia and there are no established treatments. Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) has shown promise in improving memory and cognition in MCI, Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and related dementias. We reviewed existing literature on the effect of rTMS on MCI and dementias. Methods: Comprehensive database search (Medline, Embase, Cochrane, APA PsycINFO, Web of Science, and Scopus) from 1/2000-1/2022 using keywords related to TMS, MCI, and dementia. In this presentation we report results on MCI. Results: We identified 12 randomized controlled trials of rTMS on MCI comprising 345 patients, mean ages 67.5±6.24 (rTMS) and 67.65±5.61 (controls). Diagnoses included MCI (7), vascular MCI (3), MCI-Parkinson’s Disease (1), and MCI combined with AD (1). Sites of stimulation were left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) (n=9), right DLPFC (n=1), precuneus (n=1), and left lateral frontal lobe (n=1). Daily sessions ranged from 1-30, although most frequently used was 10. rTMS parameters varied widely, with ranges of 80-120% motor threshold stimulus intensity (majority used 100%MT), 5-20Hz frequency, and 60-3000 total pulses. Of the 12 studies, 10 reported improved cognitive measures compared to control (face-name associative memory, episodic memory, immediate free recall, everyday memory, total Repeatable Battery for the Assessment of Neurological Status, Montreal Test of Cognitive Assessment, 3MS, MMSE, Trail Making Test, Clinical Global Impression-Improvement, Stroop interference, digit symbols subtest of the Wechsler Adult intelligence Scale-Revised. Two studies reported no change in vascular MCI participants. Conclusions: There is evidence that rTMS improves memory and cognition in MCI. Left DLPFC is the most common stimulation site, and 10 sessions is frequently used. There was variability in rTMS parameters of intensity and pulses. Further studies are needed to extend these promising findings. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: Cognitive impairment, Dementia, non-invasive brain stimulation, DLPFC
