N2  - Abstract Background: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has become increasingly popular to treat different types of brain diseases. However, one major challenge in real-world clinical practice is that the treatment responses to rTMS are highly variable across individuals. Neuroanatomical factors explaining the heterogeneity of rTMS effects are less investigated. In this secondary analysis, we quantified and examined the predictive matrices of estimated brain age in the responses to rTMS in elderly patients. Methods: Fifty-five elderly patients with co-occurring cognitive impairments and depression were randomly assigned to receive a 3-week treatment of either active rTMS or sham rTMS. Based on structural magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scans, estimated brain age was calculated with the morphometric features using support vector machine. “Brain Age Gap Estimation” (BrainAGE) score was computed as the difference between brain age and chronological age. Results: In the context of advanced chronological age, the rTMS responders and remitters had younger brain age than non-responders and remitters. Every additional year of BrainAGE at baseline decreased the odds of 3-week depression amelioration by ∼25.7% in responders (Odd ratio [OR] = 0.743, Nagelkerke R2 = 0.392, p = 0.045) and by ∼39.5% in remitters (OR = 0.605, Nagelkerke R2 = 0.606, p = 0.022) in active rTMS group. Conclusions: Pre-treatment BrainAGE in patients with major neurocognitive disorders may index macro-level brain features, relevant to inter-individual variability in treatment responses to rTMS. These findings highlight the need for an assessment of pre-treatment MRI-informed brain features when advising and selecting the patients for rTMS treatment. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: TMS, brain age, cortical features, randomized controlled trial
