N2  - Abstract In the last few years, repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has emerged as one of the most promising therapeutic interventions in the battle against Alzheimer’s disease (AD). The potential of this technique lies in the possibility to non-invasively promote changes in synaptic plasticity, which is altered in AD due to underlying amyloid and tau pathology. To date, treatments based on multiple rTMS sessions mostly applied over the prefrontal cortex for 2-6 weeks, provided substantial evidence of short-term beneficial effects on cognitive functions in people with AD. However, recent evidences showed that since the early phases of AD, prominent neuropathological changes are mostly distributed to posterior cortical regions of the brain affecting specifically the precuneus (PC), which is a key node of the so-called default mode network (DMN). Disconnection of the PC region precedes and contributes to the occurrence of regional brain atrophy, which becomes prominent at later disease stages and the PC activity is considered necessary for episodic memory retrieval, whose impairment represents the clinical onset of typical AD. On the basis of these evidence our group recently showed, in the context of randomized, sham-controlled, double-blinded trial performed in mild AD patients, that a two-weeks of high-frequency PC-rTMS results in an enhancement of long-term memory and in a parallel increase of neural activity within the DMN in patients with AD. Following these findings, we successfully performed a randomized phase 2 sham-controlled trial to evaluate safety and efficacy of 24-weeks PC rTMS in mild-to-moderate Alzheimer’s disease, demonstrating that non-invasive brain stimulation of the PC improves cognitive functions and activities of daily living and further suggesting that non-invasive brain stimulation may slow down disease progression in AD. Here we discuss novel findings on non-invasive brain stimulation techniques in Alzheimer’s disease and their clinical implications. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: rTMS, Alzheimer's disease, Plasticity
