N2  - Symposium title: Multifocal brain stimulation as potential treatment strategies in neurological disorders Symposium description: Inter-areal synchronization of neuronal populations is ubiquitous and is thought to be critical for coordinating neuronal communication or gating information transmission according to cognitive demands. The alteration of inter-areal coupling measured in multiple brain disorders has motivated the development of multifocal brain stimulation paradigms that try to restore brain connectivity, for instance via long-range phase synchronization. This symposium will provide an overview of the current non-invasive brain stimulation approaches attempting to normalize large-scale brain synchrony. It will introduce results of recent or on-going clinical trials that applied multifocal brain stimulation in stroke, in Alzheimer’s disease, aging and depression. This symposium will therefore highlight some promising multifocal brain stimulation approaches as novel interventional rehabilitation strategies for patients. Abstract Non-invasive brain stimulation for the treatment of depression is primed for rapid further development and progress in increasing efficacy by application of rational design. Common approaches to the treatment of depression with non-invasive brain stimulation are static with every patient receiving the same treatment. Yet, the response to stimulation is dictated by the interaction of endogenous network dynamics and the temporal structure of the stimulation waveform. Indeed, recent discoveries about how temporal and spatial activity patterns map onto specific symptom domains enable the rational design of targeted, individualized, and adaptive stimulation paradigms. In a recently completed clinical trial of transcranial alternating current stimulation in patients with psychosis, we targeted oscillation strength and functional connectivity with a repeated stimulation paradigm and a multielectrode setup. We found the hypothesized change in alpha oscillation strength when compared to sham stimulation as predicted from electric field modeling. Exploratory analysis revealed significant and lasting changes in rhythmic synchronization and changes in mood symptoms. Importantly, we found a reduction in interhemispheric frontal connectivity, a marker of depression severity, and an increase in anterior-posterior connectivity. Building on these results of successful target engagement with a multi-electrode tACS approach, we are now conducting the next generation of clinical trials that are focused on precision neuromodulation that combines temporal and spatial targeting with control of behavioral state and context during stimulation. Ongoing clinical trials in our center investigate the role of simultaneously targeting multiple spatial targets, sophisticated waveforms that target interacting frequencies in electric activity of network synchronization, and modulation of context to enhance state-dependent effects during brain stimulation with evidence-based psychotherapy. The talk will demonstrate the rationale behind these augmented targeting strategies and share latest results from these ongoing studies. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords: Depression, tACS, Alpha oscillations, Multielectrode setup
