N2  - Abstract Introduction: Traumatic brain injury (TBI) is a severe cause of disability with long-term sequelae (Ponsford et al. 2014). Standard neurorehabilitation treatments may not be sufficient to guarantee a good quality of life. Treatments with rTMS and tDCS are promising therapeutic options for neuropsychiatric conditions, including TBI sequelae (Lefaucheur et al. 2017; 2014). This study aims at providing a systematic review and meta-analysis on the effectiveness of rTMS and tDCS on post-TBI symptoms. Methods: Five different databases were consulted: MEDLINE, Cochrane Library, EMBASE, PsychINFO and Web of Science. 12 randomized controlled trials (RCT) that assessed the effects of rTMS or tDCS versus sham stimulation on clinical scales and questionnaires measuring post-TBI symptoms were selected. Symptoms were clustered into four groups: depression, anxiety, headache and cognitive dysfunctions. Standardized Mean Changes pre- and post-treatment were calculated. Correlated and Hierarchical Effects models were generated. Subgroup analyses considered the potential moderating effects of multiple variables (TBI severity, NIBS technique, stimulated hemisphere, stimulation frequency and intensity, total number of pulses, assessment time point). Results: There were only few and heterogeneous studies on the effects of rTMS and tDCS on TBI sequelae, with generally small sample sizes. Most studies targeted the DLPFC. Overall, effects of NIBS on the four symptoms clusters were small and did not reach statistical significance. Moderator variables did not have an influence on these results. Conclusions: There is little evidence for effectiveness of rTMS and tDCS concerning TBI sequelae treatment. Ineffectiveness of NIBS treatments might be related to a lack of personalization or insufficient stimulation dose (Cole et al. 2020). While rTMS and tDCS continue to emerge as promising tools for the treatment of neuropsychiatric conditions, more evidence should be gathered in the field of TBI sequelae. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: rTMS, tDCS, TBI, meta-analysis
